%md
###Overview
In this notebook we will apply pyspark's mllib implementation of k-means clustering to group individual grid points together in a dataset based on similar climate regimes. We will do so for this particular example using the standard deviation and skewness of surface air temperature time series, as Loikith et al. 2013 had done.

%md
####Accessing the Data
For this example, we will be using the NASA MERRA reanalysis daily mean surface air temperature dataset. The spatial resolution is 0.5 degrees latitude by 0.67 degrees longitude, with a temporal coverage of 1979-2011. The raw data has already been subset into one quarter of the globe primarily spanning North America and includes only days falling in January. We will use the netCDF4 python library to directly access the data as follows:

paragraphs.title: Step 1: Load the Data from The netcdf File
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from netCDF4 import Dataset
nc = Dataset('/data/cluster-local/notebook_data/pdf_clustering/tas_MERRA_NA_daily_January_1979-2011.nc')
tas = nc.variables['tasjan'][:]
lats = nc.variables['lat'][:]
lons = nc.variables['lon'][:]

%md
####Preparing the Data
Before applying kmeans clustering, we must properly prepare the data first. This entails converting the raw temperature values to anomalies (deviations from the mean climatological state) and then removing longterm linear trends.

paragraphs.title: Step 2: Calculate temperature anomalies and Remove Longterm Linear Trends
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
import numpy as np
import scipy.signal as signal

def detrend_daily_data(data, years, month):
    '''
    Detrend a daily climate time series for one month.
    This will remove the climatology for each day as well as directly remove
    longterm linear trends at each grid point.

    Input:
        data - 3D numpy array with dimensions (days, lats, lons)
        years - 1D numpy array of years spanning the time series
        month - The month for the given time series (1-Jan, 12-Dec)

    Output:
        detrended_data - Detrended time series (days, lats, lons)

    Note: February (month=2) not supported yet.
    '''
    # Reshape the data based on the month
    days_by_month = [31, 29, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31, 31, 30, 31, 30, 31]
    mdays = days_by_month[month-1]
    nyears = len(years)

    # TODO: Support for Feb if desired
    if month == 2:
        raise ValueError('February (month=2) not currently supported')

    # Reshape to (year, day of year, lat, lon) to easily calculate
    # daily climatology
    data = data.reshape(nyears, mdays, *data.shape[1:])

    # Subtract daily climatology from original data to obtain anomalies
    clim = data.mean(axis=0)
    data -= clim

    # Remove longterm linear trends
    data = data.reshape(mdays*nyears, *data.shape[2:])
    detrended_data = signal.detrend(data, axis=0)
    return detrended_data

years = np.arange(1979, 2012)
month = 1
detrended_data = detrend_daily_data(tas, years, month)

%md
####Determining The Inputs For KMeans
For k-means clustering, we may choose to use an arbitrary number of variables defined at each grid point as our input. In this example we will use two PDF moments (Standard Deviation and Skewness) as our input, which are calculated from the detrended anomaly timeseries at each grid point below:

paragraphs.title: Step 3: Calculate the PDF moments
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from scipy.stats import stats

def calc_moments(data):
    '''
    Determine standard deviation and skewness of input data

    Input:
        data - 3D numpy array with dimensions (days, lats, lons)

    Output:
        std, skew - 2nd and 3rd PDF moments respectively for
        each grid point (lats, lons)
    '''
    std = np.std(data, axis=0)
    skew = stats.skew(data, axis=0)
    return std, skew
    
std, sk = calc_moments(detrended_data)

%md
####Perform KMeans Clustering On The PDF Moments
We are now finally ready to perform k-means clustering using the PDF moments calculated in the previous step as our input. The choice of k is in fact an arbitrary one, but for our purposes we will find that k=5 should produce the most physically meaningful clusters. Here we will use pyspark's mllib implementation of k-means clustering to get the job done.

paragraphs.title: Step 4: Perform K-means clustering on the PDF Moments
paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
from scipy.cluster.vq import whiten
from pyspark.mllib.clustering import KMeans

def kmeans_clustering(k, m1, m2, normalized=True, **kwargs):
    '''
    Perform k-means clustering

    Input:
        k - Number of clusters (int)
        m1, m2 - The PDF moments for each grid point (lat, lon) or (grid points)
        (Optional) normalized - If true normalize inputs before clustering
        (Optional) kwargs - See scipy.cluster.vq.kmeans2 for additional kwargs.

    Output:
        centroids - locations of cluster centroids in m1, m2 space (k, 2)
        labels - index array which assigns each grid point to a centroid
    '''
    # Ensure moments are 1D before clustering. The input to kmeans must
    # have a shape of (m, n) where m is the number of grid points and
    # n is the number of dimensions (in this case 1 for each moment)
    m1 = m1.ravel()
    m2 = m2.ravel()
    if normalized:
        input_array = np.array(whiten(zip(m1, m2))) # normalizing data
    else:
        input_array = np.array(zip(m1, m2))

    rdd = sc.parallelize(input_array)
    model = KMeans.train(rdd, k, **kwargs)
    centroids = np.array(model.centers)
    labels = np.array(model.predict(rdd).collect())
    return centroids, labels
    
k = 5
centroids, labels = kmeans_clustering(k, std, sk, normalized=False,
                                      maxIterations=300,
                                      initializationMode='kmeans',
                                      seed=0)

%md
####Visualizing the Results
#####Maps
There are two outputs from k-means clustering. First we have `centroids`, which are a set of points defined in n-dimensional space representing the locations of the cluster centroids. In this case, we entered two input variables into k-means with k=5, so this variable is an array of 5 points denoting (Standard Deviation, Skewness). The `labels` array contains the cluster number assigned to each grid point which are denoted by the respective indices of the centroids array (eg 0-4). We will now produce a figure which contains (1) The cluster numbers color coded on a map (2) A scatter plot of the clusters over the entire grid with the centroid locations denoted, and (3) contour maps of standard deviation and skewness. The resulting figure should be consistent with Loikith et al., 2013.

paragraphs.title: Step 5: Visualize the results
paragraphs.text: %pyspark import matplotlib as mpl mpl.use('Agg') import matplotlib.pyplot as plt import cStringIO import base64 from mpl_toolkits.basemap import Basemap def show(p): img = cStringIO.StringIO() p.savefig(img, format='png') imgStr = "data:image/png;base64," imgStr += base64.b64encode(img.getvalue().strip()) print "%html " def visualize_clusters(centroids, labels, moments, lats, lons, ptitle=''): ''' Visualize the k clusters on a map. Input: centroids - locations of cluster centroids (k, 2) labels - group number for each grid point (gridpoints) moments - dict where values are moment numpy arrays and keys are the name of each moment (eg. 'Skewness') lats, lons - 1 or 2D numpy arrays of lat/lon information (Optional) title - Plot title (string) ''' if lats.ndim == 1: nx, ny = len(lons), len(lats) else: nx, ny = lons.shape[1], lats.shape[0] # Sort data by first moment (usually standard deviation) sortidx = np.argsort(centroids[:, 0]) clusters = np.zeros(nx*ny) k = centroids.shape[0] for i in np.arange(k): clusters[labels==sortidx[i]] = i # Reshape so clusters are on a 2D grid clusters = clusters.reshape(ny, nx) + 1 # Make Plots fig, plot_grid = plt.subplots(nrows=2, ncols=2) fig.set_size_inches((11, 7)) plt.subplots_adjust(wspace=0.2, hspace=0.2) # Set up the color scaling cmap = plt.cm.rainbow norm = mpl.colors.BoundaryNorm(1 + np.arange(k+1), cmap.N) # Upper Left: Map of clusters lon_min = lons.min() lon_max = lons.max() lat_min = lats.min() lat_max = lats.max() m = Basemap(projection='cyl', llcrnrlat=lat_min, urcrnrlat=lat_max, llcrnrlon=lon_min, urcrnrlon=lon_max, resolution='l') m.ax = plot_grid[0, 0] if lats.ndim == 1: lons, lats = np.meshgrid(lons, lats) x, y = m(lons, lats) clevs = 0.5 + np.arange(k+1) m.drawcoastlines(linewidth=1) m.drawcountries(linewidth=.75) m.contourf(x, y, clusters, levels=clevs, cmap=cmap, norm=norm, alpha=0.5) m.ax.set_title('Clusters') # Upper Right: Scatter Plot of clusters ax = plot_grid[0,1] m1, m2 = moments.values() m1 = m1.ravel() m2 = m2.ravel() name1, name2 = moments.keys() clusters = clusters.ravel() ax.scatter(m1, m2, s=12, edgecolor='none', c=clusters, marker='o', cmap=cmap, norm=norm, alpha=0.5) ax.set_title('Cluster Legend') ax.set_aspect('equal') # Label each cluster centroid for i in 1 + np.arange(k): xm = m1[clusters==i].mean() ym = m2[clusters==i].mean() ax.plot(xm, ym, marker='$%d$' %(i), markersize=12, color='k') ax.set_xlabel(name1) ax.set_ylabel(name2) # Bottom: Plot moments for ax, moment, name in zip(plot_grid[1, :], moments.values(), moments.keys()): m.ax = ax m.drawcoastlines(linewidth=1) m.drawcountries(linewidth=.75) cs = m.contourf(x, y, moment, 20) m.colorbar(cs, location='bottom', ax=ax) m.ax.set_title(name) # Title and save the figure fig.suptitle(ptitle) show(plt) moments = {'Standard Deviation':std, 'Skewness':sk} title = 'MERRA Jan. Surface Temperature (1979-2011)' visualize_clusters(centroids, labels, moments, lats, lons, ptitle=title)

PDFs

Given these results so far, are the shapes of the underlying distributions for each cluster consistent with what we expect? To find out, we will approximate the PDFs using histograms with 200 bins. We will use the following code to define these histograms at each gridpoint:

paragraphs.text:
%pyspark
import numpy.ma as ma

hist = []
bins = np.histogram(detrended_data, bins=152)[1]
for i in range(len(lats)):
    for j in range(len(lons)):
        hist.append(np.histogram(detrended_data[:, i, j], bins=bins, density=False)[0])
hist = np.log10(hist) - np.log10(detrended_data.shape[0])

def visualize_histograms(centroids, labels, hist, bins, units='K', ptitle=''):
    '''
    Plot PDFs for each cluster

    Input:
        centroids - locations of cluster centroids (k, 2)
        labels - group number for each grid point (gridpoints)
        hist - Array containing histogram info for each grid point (gridpoints, nbins)
        bins - Bin edges array (nbins)
        (Optional) units - Units of the source data (string)
        (Optional) ptitle - Plot title (string)
    '''
    # Sort data by first moment (usually standard deviation)
    clusters = labels + 1
    k = centroids.shape[0]

    # Set up the color scaling
    cmap = plt.cm.rainbow
    norm = mpl.colors.Normalize(vmin=1, vmax=k)
    plt.figure(figsize=(8.5, 5.5))

    # Bottom: Cluster PDFs
    anom = 0.5*(bins + np.roll(bins, -1))[:-1]
    colorpicker = mpl.cm.ScalarMappable(norm=norm, cmap=cmap)
    for i in range(1, k+1):
        vals = hist[clusters==i]
        vals = ma.masked_array(vals, mask=np.isinf(vals))
        pdf = vals.mean(axis=0)
        std = vals.std(axis=0)
        color = colorpicker.to_rgba(i)
        plt.plot(anom, pdf, color=color)
        plt.fill_between(anom, pdf-std, pdf+std, facecolor=color,
                        edgecolor=color, alpha=0.25)
                        
    plt.xlabel('Anomaly [%s]' %units)
    #plt.yticks([])
    plt.ylim(ymin=-3.0, ymax=0)
    plt.title('Cluster PDFs - %s' %ptitle)
    show(plt)

visualize_histograms(centroids, labels, hist, bins, ptitle='MERRA')

%md
####Exercise: Using histogram bins as input to KMeans

So far we have demonstrated how to perform KMeans clustering using two aspects of PDF shape (standard deviation and skewness) as our main inputs. What if we instead wanted to account for *all* aspects of PDF shape to determine the clusters? Create a modified version of the `kmeans_clustering()` function shown above that accepts the frequencies of each bin of a histogram at each gridpoint as an input instead of the two moments, and use it to perform KMeans clustering with the provided MERRA data and k=5 clusters. You may use the histograms already generated in the variable `hist`. Plot your results using calls to `visualize_clusters()` and `visualize_histograms()`. Are these results similar to those shown when using two moments as inputs to KMeans instead?
